Results._refObjectName: [Prod Success] Move Login Event generation code out of plugin implementation
Results.Description:
Done
  • The code responsible for generating Login events has been moved to a location where a Login event is always fired when a user logs in to a Brightspace instance
  • The existing plugin has been deleted
  • All documentation referring to the old plugin has been removed
Notes

Currently the code responsible for generating Login events lives within a plugin implementation:
  • Class: D2L.LP.Auth.LoginActions.LoginEventAction
  • Assembly: D2L.LP.Auth
  • Plugin Extension Point: D2L.LP.Login.Domain.ILoginAction
Because plugins can be configured (turned on/off) this leads to a data loss scenario when this plugin implementation isn't included in an override for a particular client.

There is a OI JIRA ticket (https://jira.dev.d2l/browse/BI-954) to determine how many Insights customers this currently affects. There is a small chance that this story may not be done if the current client impact is very small.
Results.Name: [Prod Success] Move Login Event generation code out of plugin implementation

Results._refObjectName: [Prod Success] Course access event should not fire when a student attempts to access inactive course content
Results.Description:
Steps to reproduce:
  • Enroll a student in a course for which the end date is in the past
  • Create a content topic and note the url for accessing the content topic
  • Log in as the student and directly access the url for the content topic
    • Note that a “Page Not Found” error is displayed and the course name is still present in the “Select a Course…” menu
  • Click the dropdown arrow in the “Select a course” menu
  • This causes the event with an empty role Id to be fired
 
Conceptually this scenario could occur if a student has a content topic bookmarked, and attempts to return to that topic after the course has ended, and then accesses one of their other courses through the menu. Loading the menu appears to cause a partial page load with the org unit context of the course that has ended and this triggers the event.
 
It’s worth noting that this issue doesn’t exist when accessing the course homepage directly through the url outside of the course availability dates because when this page is accessed, the org unit context is removed from the page and a “Not authorized” error is displayed instead.

This issue could be fixed by removing the org unit context from the page when a student attempts to access a course which is inaccessible, or by doing some extra role validation prior to firing the event
Results.Name: [Prod Success] Course access event should not fire when a student attempts to access inactive course content

Results._refObjectName: [S3] S3 is capable of being included in Copy Course Components
Results.Description:
Title was: Add S3ModelCopyManager to S3 (to support copying of a predictive model during Copy Course Components)

Done:
  • New class (S3ModelCopyManager) exists with corresponding interface
    • This class must exist in the S3 solution/repository (Important!)
  • Needs to expose functionality to copy all relevant details of an S3 predictive model
    • Extract logic of Save () method from ModelConfigurationController.cs in D2L.AP.S3.Administration.Web.Desktop.Controllers
    • ModelConfigurationController.cs will then use the S3ModelCopyManager
      • Rather than duplicate the code
  • Consider and handle appropriately
    • Date range
      • In S3 case: do nothing
      • In CCC case: use the date range from the existing course (that is being copied into)
    • Grade range
      • Likely just preserve grade range from copied model
    • Errors
      • E.g. Historic course(s) not meeting status requirements
      • Log a warning (indicating what went wrong) and don't copy the model
  • Unit tests for S3ModelCopyManager
  • Exploratory testing to confirm that S3 model copying works as before (no functionality changes)
Results.Name: [S3] S3 is capable of being included in Copy Course Components

        • See the previous SPIKE for more details

      • SelectTool()

  • In select_tools_control.xml

GENERAL

    • Copy all is the much more common case
    • We should log an error/warning if the S3 model cannot be copied for a given reason
      • Tool not available
      • User does not have permission
TEST CONSIDERATIONS
  • Proper testing of entire workflow, including edge cases
    • Copy All Components
    • Select Components

    • Copy S3 Model with course info

Results._refObjectName: [Data Export] API access to data (Metron Facade)
Results.Description:
We want customers to be able to access their data extracts *only* via Metron.  To do this, we'll build a Facade API in Metron for the LE API that actually extracts the data.

AC:
* 4. Use Metron as a façade for this API by creating Metron APIs that, given OAuth token,
a. Request Report
b. Poll for report generation status (returning link to report location which will be the customer’s LE web server)
>>When customers want to have API access to data, they do it through Metron.
NOTE: The *data* doesn’t flow through Metron – just the call routing.  So – no data residency, legal, or bandwidth-cost issues.

5. Add an output format option for all Metron routes.
a. For current generic agg’n routes, if anything but json is requested, return “Not supported”
b. For LE/Warehouse data access routes, if anything but ‘csv file’ is requested, return “Not supported”
>>This offers a consistent interface without requiring any kind of data translation.




BACKGROUND
With some good input from Draco/Viktor, technically, we’re thinking the following for the approach to API’ing access to LE/Warehouse data extracts.  (This is the first time I’ve run this past James/Jamie who may have other thoughts too.)

Capability:
- Allow customers (and FRAs) to request reports/data extracts from the LE/Warehouse via API.
- D2L/Craig acceptance criteria: Make it as seamless as possible for customers who code against our API to migrate to a future Metron-based API.

<Orcavengers Current slice work>
1. Build API functions into the LE API that do:
a. Request report
b. Poll for report generation status (returning link to report location)
2. Store generated report files (CSVs) in the LE.
3. Use these for FRAs and don’t advertise them to customers.  (Internal, unstable)

<Orcavengers Near future slice work>
4. Use Metron as a façade for this API by creating Metron APIs that, given OAuth token,
a. Request Report
b. Poll for report generation status (returning link to report location which will be the customer’s LE web server)
>>When customers want to have API access to data, they do it through Metron.
NOTE: The *data* doesn’t flow through Metron – just the call routing.  So – no data residency, legal, or bandwidth-cost issues.

5. Add an output format option for all Metron routes.
a. For current generic agg’n routes, if anything but json is requested, return “Not supported”
b. For LE/Warehouse data access routes, if anything but ‘csv file’ is requested, return “Not supported”
>>This offers a consistent interface without requiring any kind of data translation.

<Distant work>
6. Update this data to come from BDP / events, using the same access interface on Metron.


Questions:
1. Would we ever tell customers about the LE-based API functions?  I propose NO - Instead, we could use “API access to data” as leverage to get customers onto the BDP, even before the actual data source is the BDP.
2. Am I wrong about there being no legal-type concerns here?
3. Other concerns?
Results.Name: [Data Export] API access to data (Metron Facade)

Results._refObjectName: [Class Engagement] - Send email to user's prefered location (internal vs external email address)
Results.Description:
There are currently no valence routes that expose the user's notification preferences, therefore our FRA has no way of knowing which email address (internal vs external) to send class emails to.

Acceptance Criteria:
- Expose a new route or augment an existing route which displays the user's notification preferences (internal email, external email (with value), or no email preference configured.
- Consume the new route from within the parent FRA, and pass the information down as part of the user objects, or something functionally equivalent.
